<A NAME="eolPage122"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following is a description of the methods used to determine the fair values of significant
	assets and liabilities presented above:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Cash and due from banks, interest-bearing deposits with other banks and federal funds
	sold
</U>
	&#150; The carrying amount of these assets is a reasonable estimate of fair value based on the short-term nature of these assets. The $30.0 million adjustment is the cash settlement paid to Liberty on the closing date. The Company also paid
	off the Liberty $52.5 million SBLF preferred stock at the acquisition date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Investment securities
</U>
	&#150; Investment securities
	were acquired from Liberty with a $9.8 million adjustment to market value based upon quoted market prices. This adjustment is primarily the result of marking the held-to-maturity securities to fair market value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Loans
</U>
	&#150; Fair values for loans were based on a discounted cash flow methodology that considered factors including the type of loan
	and related collateral, classification status, fixed or variable interest rate, term of loan and whether or not the loan was amortizing, and current discount rates. The discount rates used for loans are based on current market rates for new
	originations of comparable loans and include adjustments for liquidity concerns.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company evaluated $1.67 billion of the loans
	purchased in conjunction with the acquisition in accordance with the provisions of FASB ASC Topic 310-20,
<I>
	Nonrefundable Fees and Other Costs,
</I>
	and were recorded with a $62.1 million discount. As a result, the fair value discount on these loans
	is being accreted into interest income over the weighted average life of the loans using a constant yield method. The remaining $162.4 million of loans evaluated were considered purchased credit impaired loans within the provisions of FASB ASC Topic
	310-30,
<I>
	Loans and Debt Securities Acquired with Deteriorated Credit Quality,
</I>
	and were recorded with a $41.9 million discount. These purchase credit impaired loans will recognize interest income through accretion of the difference between the
	carrying amount of the loans and the expected cash flows.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Bank premises and equipment
</U>
	&#150; Bank premises and equipment were
	acquired from Liberty with a $5.4 million adjustment to market value. This represents the difference between current appraisal completed in connection with the acquisition and book value acquired.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Foreclosed assets held for sale not covered by loss share
</U>
	&#150; These assets are presented at the estimated fair values that
	management expects to receive when the properties are sold, net of related costs of disposal.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Cash value of life insurance
</U>
	&#150;
	Cash value of life insurance was acquired from Liberty at market value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Accrued interest receivable
</U>
	&#150; Accrued interest
	receivable was acquired from Liberty at market value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Deferred tax asset
</U>
	&#150; The current and deferred income tax assets and
	liabilities are recorded to reflect the differences in the carrying values of the acquired assets and assumed liabilities for financial reporting purposes and the cost basis for federal income tax purposes, at the Company&#146;s statutory federal
	and state income tax rate of 39.225%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Goodwill
</U>
	&#150; The consideration paid as a result of the acquisition exceeded the fair
	value of the assets acquired; therefore, the Company recorded $216.1 million of goodwill.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Core deposit intangible
</U>
	&#150; This
	intangible asset represents the value of the relationships that Liberty Bank had with its deposit customers. The fair value of this intangible asset was estimated based on a discounted cash flow methodology that gave appropriate consideration to
	expected customer attrition rates, cost of the deposit base, and the net maintenance cost attributable to customer deposits. The Company recorded $13.9 million of core deposit intangible.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Deposits
</U>
	&#150; The fair values used for the demand and savings deposits that comprise the transaction accounts acquired, by definition
	equal the amount payable on demand at the acquisition date. The $913,000 fair value adjustment applied for time deposits is because the estimated weighted average interest rate of Liberty&#146;s certificates of deposits were estimated to be slightly
	below the current market rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Securities sold under agreements to repurchase
</U>
	&#150; Securities sold under agreements to
	repurchase were acquired from Liberty at market value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	122
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage123"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	FHLB borrowed funds
</U>
	&#150; The fair value of FHLB borrowed funds is estimated based on
	borrowing rates currently available to the Company for borrowings with similar terms and maturities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Accrued interest payable and
	other liabilities
</U>
	&#150; The fair value used represents the accrual of certain costs including change in control agreements which were incurred in connection with the merger.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Subordinated debentures
</U>
	&#150; Subordinated debentures were acquired from Liberty at market value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The unaudited pro-forma combined consolidated financial information presents how the combined financial information of HBI and Liberty might
	have appeared had the businesses actually been combined. The following schedule represents the unaudited pro-forma combined financial information as of the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, assuming the acquisition was completed as of
	January&nbsp;1, 2013:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The unaudited pro-forma consolidated financial information is presented for illustrative purposes only and
	does not indicate the financial results of the combined company had the companies actually been combined at the beginning of the period presented and had the impact of possible revenue enhancements and expense efficiencies, among other factors, been
	considered and, accordingly, does not attempt to predict or suggest future results. It also does not necessarily reflect what the historical results of the combined company would have been had the companies been combined during this period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	FDIC-Assisted Acquisitions - Other Matters
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In an FDIC-assisted acquisition, we may acquire certain assets and assume certain liabilities of the former institution with or without a
	loss-share agreement with the FDIC. Any regulatory agreements or orders that existed for the former institution do not apply to the assuming institution. We, as the assuming institution, are evaluated separately by our regulators and any weaknesses
	of the former institution are considered in a separate evaluation. Also, the loss share agreement helps to mitigate any weaknesses that may have existed in the former institution.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	123

<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	3. Investment Securities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amortized cost and estimated fair value of investment securities that are classified as available-for-sale and
	held-to-maturity are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_59"></A>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="92%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="70%">
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="1%">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>

<A NAME="eolPage125"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Assets, principally investment securities, having an amortized cost of approximately $1.25
	billion and $1.23 billion at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, were pledged to secure public deposits and for other purposes required or permitted by law. Also, investment securities pledged as collateral for repurchase agreements
	totaled approximately $128.4 million and $176.5 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amortized cost and
	estimated fair value of securities classified as available-for-sale and held-to-maturity at December&nbsp;31, 2015, by contractual maturity, are shown below. Expected maturities will differ from contractual maturities because borrowers may have the
	right to call or prepay obligations with or without call or prepayment penalties.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For purposes of the maturity tables, mortgage-backed securities, which are not due at a single maturity date,
	have been allocated over maturity groupings based on anticipated maturities. The mortgage-backed securities may mature earlier than their
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	weighted-average
</FONT>
	contractual maturities because of principal
	prepayments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, approximately $4.0 million, in available-for-sale securities were sold. The
	gross realized gains on these sales totaled approximately $4,000. There were no losses on the available-for-sale securities sold. The income tax expense/benefit to net security gains and losses was 39.225% of the gross amounts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, no available-for-sale securities were sold.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, $282.5 million of available-for-sale securities were sold. The gross realized gains on these
	sales totaled approximately $111,000. There were no losses on the available-for-sale securities sold. The income tax expense/benefit to net security gains and losses was 39.225% of the gross amounts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, there were $309.0 million, $356.8 million and $114.6 million of held-to-maturity securities,
	respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company evaluates all securities quarterly to determine if any unrealized losses are deemed to be other than temporary.
	In completing these evaluations the Company follows the requirements of FASB ASC 320,
<I>
	Investments - Debt and Equity Securities.
</I>
	Certain investment securities are valued less than their historical cost. These declines are primarily the result
	of the rate for these investments yielding less than current market rates. Based on evaluation of available evidence, management believes the declines in fair value for these securities are temporary. The Company does not intend to sell or believe
	it will be required to sell these investments before recovery of their amortized cost bases, which may be maturity. Should the impairment of any of these securities become other than temporary, the cost basis of the investment will be reduced and
	the resulting loss recognized in net income in the period the other-than-temporary impairment is identified.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had approximately $1.2 million in unrealized losses, which were in continuous loss positions for more than twelve months. Excluding impairment write downs taken in prior periods, the Company&#146;s assessments
	indicated that the cause of the market depreciation was primarily the change in interest rates and not the issuer&#146;s financial condition, or downgrades by rating agencies. In addition, approximately 77.6% of the Company&#146;s investment
	portfolio matures in five years or less. As a result, the Company has the ability and intent to hold such securities until maturity.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	125
</P>

	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, the Company had approximately $1.3 million in
	unrealized losses, which were in continuous loss positions for more than twelve months. Excluding impairment write downs taken in prior periods, the Company&#146;s assessments indicated that the cause of the market depreciation was primarily the
	change in interest rates and not the issuer&#146;s financial condition, or downgrades by rating agencies. In addition, approximately 80.5% of the Company&#146;s investment portfolio matures in five years or less. As a result, the Company has the
	ability and intent to hold such securities until maturity.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	have been in a continuous loss position as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014:

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	4. Loans Receivable Not Covered by Loss Share
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The various categories of loans not covered by loss share are summarized as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>

<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="76%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" ALIGN="CENTER">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company sold $7.7 million of the guaranteed portion of
	certain SBA loans, which resulted in a gain of approximately $541,000. During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, the Company sold $1.3 million of the guaranteed portion of certain SBA loans, which resulted in a gain of approximately $183,000.
	During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, the Company sold $2.0 million of the guaranteed portion of certain SBA loans, which resulted in a gain of approximately $135,000.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Mortgage loans held for resale of approximately $38.9 million and $33.1 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, are included
	in residential 1-4 family loans. Mortgage loans held for sale are carried at the lower of cost or fair value, determined using an aggregate basis. Gains and losses resulting from sales of mortgage loans are recognized when the respective loans are
	sold to investors. Gains and losses are determined by the difference between the selling price and the carrying amount of the loans sold, net of discounts collected or paid. The Company obtains forward commitments to sell mortgage loans to reduce
	market risk on mortgage loans in the process of origination and mortgage loans held for sale. The forward commitments acquired by the Company for mortgage loans in process of origination are considered mandatory forward commitments. Because these
	commitments are structured on a mandatory basis, the Company is required to substitute another loan or to buy back the commitment if the original loan does not fund. These commitments are derivative instruments and their fair values at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 were not material.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	127
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	5. Loans Receivable Covered by FDIC Loss Share
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company evaluated loans purchased in conjunction with the acquisitions under purchase and assumption agreements with the
	FDIC for impairment in accordance with the provisions of FASB ASC Topic 310-30. Purchased covered loans are considered impaired if there is evidence of credit deterioration since origination and if it is probable that not all contractually required
	payments will be collected.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 for the Company:

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The acquired loans were grouped into pools based on common risk characteristics and were recorded at their
	estimated fair values, which incorporated estimated credit losses at the acquisition dates. These loan pools are systematically reviewed by the Company to determine material changes in cash flow estimates from those identified at the time of the
	acquisition. Techniques used in determining risk of loss are similar to the Centennial non-covered loan portfolio, with most focus being placed on those loan pools which include the larger loan relationships and those loan pools which exhibit higher
	risk characteristics. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, $3.3 million and $22.5 million, respectively, were accruing loans past due 90 days or more.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	128
</P>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Allowance for Loan Losses and Credit Quality for Non-Covered Loans
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following tables present the balance in the allowance for loan losses for the non-covered loan portfolio for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, and the allowance for loan losses and recorded investment in loans not covered by loss share based on portfolio segment by impairment method as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. Allocation of a portion of the allowance to one type
	of loans does not preclude its availability to absorb losses in other categories. Additionally, the Company&#146;s discounts for credit losses on non-covered loans acquired were $139.5 million, $174.6 million and $81.7 million at December&nbsp;31,
	2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following tables present the balance in the allowance for loan losses for the non-covered
	loan portfolio for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, and the allowance for loan losses and recorded investment in loans not covered by loss share based on portfolio segment by impairment method as of December&nbsp;31, 2014. Allocation of a
	portion of the allowance to one type of loans does not preclude its availability to absorb losses in other categories.
</P>

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following tables present the balance in the allowance for loan losses for the non-covered
	loan portfolio for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, and the allowance for loan losses and recorded investment in loans not covered by loss share based on portfolio segment by impairment method as of December&nbsp;31, 2013. Allocation of a
	portion of the allowance to one type of loans does not preclude its availability to absorb losses in other categories.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<I>
	Note:
</I>
	Purchased non-covered loans acquired with deteriorated credit quality are accounted for on a pooled basis under ASC 310-30. All of these pools are currently considered to be performing resulting in none of the purchased non-covered loans acquired
	with deteriorated credit quality being classified as non-covered impaired loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>

<I>
	Note
</I>
	:
	Purchased non-covered loans acquired with deteriorated credit quality are accounted for on a pooled basis under ASC 310-30. All of these pools are currently considered to be performing resulting in none of the purchased non-covered loans acquired
	with deteriorated credit quality being classified as non-covered impaired loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2014.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Note
</I>
	:
	Purchased non-covered loans acquired with deteriorated credit quality are accounted for on a pooled basis under ASC 310-30. All of these pools are currently considered to be performing resulting in none of the purchased non-covered loans acquired
	with deteriorated credit quality being classified as non-covered impaired loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	136
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage137"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Interest recognized on non-covered impaired loans during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015,
	2014 and 2013 was approximately $2.1 million, $2.7 million and $3.9 million, respectively. The amount of interest recognized on non-covered impaired loans on the cash basis is not materially different than the accrual basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Credit Quality Indicators.
</I>
	As part of the on-going monitoring of the credit quality of the Company&#146;s loan portfolio, management
	tracks certain credit quality indicators including trends related to (i)&nbsp;the risk rating of loans, (ii)&nbsp;the level of classified loans, (iii)&nbsp;net charge-offs, (iv)&nbsp;non-performing loans and (v)&nbsp;the general economic conditions
	in Arkansas, Florida and Alabama.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company utilizes a risk rating matrix to assign a risk rating to each of its loans. Loans are rated
	on a scale from 1 to 8. Descriptions of the general characteristics of the 8 risk ratings are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 1 &#150; Excellent.
</I>
	&nbsp;Loans in this category are to persons or entities of unquestionable financial strength, a highly liquid financial position, with collateral that is liquid and well
	margined.&nbsp;These borrowers have performed without question on past obligations, and the Bank expects their performance to continue.&nbsp;Internally generated cash flow covers current maturities of long-term debt by a substantial
	margin.&nbsp;Loans secured by bank certificates of deposit and savings accounts, with appropriate holds placed on the accounts, are to be rated in this category.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 2 &#150; Good.
</I>
	&nbsp;These are loans to persons or entities with strong financial condition and above-average liquidity that have previously satisfactorily handled their obligations with the
	Bank.&nbsp;Collateral securing the Bank&#146;s debt is margined in accordance with policy guidelines.&nbsp;Internally generated cash flow covers current maturities of long-term debt more than adequately.&nbsp;Unsecured loans to individuals supported
	by strong financial statements and on which repayment is satisfactory may be included in this classification.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 3 &#150; Satisfactory.
</I>
	&nbsp;Loans to persons or entities with an average financial condition, adequate collateral margins, adequate cash flow to service long-term debt, and net worth comprised mainly
	of fixed assets are included in this category.&nbsp;These entities are minimally profitable now, with projections indicating continued profitability into the foreseeable future.&nbsp;Closely held corporations or businesses where a majority of the
	profits are withdrawn by the owners or paid in dividends are included in this rating category.&nbsp;Overall, these loans are basically sound.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 4 &#150; Watch.
</I>
	Borrowers who have marginal cash flow, marginal profitability or have experienced an unprofitable year and a declining financial condition characterize these loans.&nbsp;The borrower
	has in the past satisfactorily handled debts with the Bank, but in recent months has either been late, delinquent in making payments, or made sporadic payments.&nbsp;While the Bank continues to be adequately secured, margins have decreased or are
	decreasing, despite the borrower&#146;s continued satisfactory condition.&nbsp;Other characteristics of borrowers in this class include inadequate credit information, weakness of financial statement and repayment capacity, but with collateral that
	appears to limit exposure.&nbsp;Included in this category are loans to borrowers in industries that are experiencing elevated risk.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 5 &#150; Other Loans Especially Mentioned (&#147;OLEM&#148;)
</I>
	.&nbsp;A loan criticized as OLEM has potential weaknesses that deserve management&#146;s close attention.&nbsp;If left uncorrected, these
	potential weaknesses may result in deterioration of the repayment prospects for the asset or in the institution&#146;s credit position at some future date.&nbsp;OLEM assets are not adversely classified and do not expose the institution to sufficient
	risk to warrant adverse classification.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 6 &#150; Substandard.
</I>
	&nbsp;A loan classified as substandard is inadequately protected by the sound worth and paying capacity of the borrower or the collateral pledged.&nbsp;Loss potential, while
	existing in the aggregate amount of substandard loans, does not have to exist in individual assets.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	137
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage138"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 7 &#150; Doubtful.
</I>
	&nbsp;A loan classified as doubtful has all the weaknesses inherent in a loan classified as substandard with the added characteristic that the weaknesses make collection or
	liquidation in full, on the basis of currently existing facts, conditions, and values, highly questionable and improbable.&nbsp;These are poor quality loans in which neither the collateral, if any, nor the financial condition of the borrower
	presently ensure collectability in full in a reasonable period of time; in fact, there is permanent impairment in the collateral securing the loan.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="13%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Risk rating 8 &#150; Loss.
</I>
	Assets classified as loss are considered uncollectible and of such little value that the continuance as bankable assets is not warranted.&nbsp;This classification does not mean that the
	asset has absolutely no recovery or salvage value, but rather, it is not practical or desirable to defer writing off this basically worthless asset, even though partial recovery may occur in the future.&nbsp;This classification is based upon current
	facts, not probabilities.&nbsp;Assets classified as loss should be charged-off in the period in which they became uncollectible.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	(excluding loans accounted for under ASC Topic 310-30) by class as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014:
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage139"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Loans may be classified, but not considered impaired, due to one of the following reasons:
	(1)&nbsp;The Company has established minimum dollar amount thresholds for loan impairment testing. All loans over $2.0 million that are rated 5 &#150; 8 are individually assessed for impairment on a quarterly basis. Loans rated 5 &#150; 8 that fall
	under the threshold amount are not individually tested for impairment and therefore are not included in impaired loans; (2)&nbsp;of the loans that are above the threshold amount and tested for impairment, after testing, some are considered to not be
	impaired and are not included in impaired loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following is a presentation of non-covered loans by class and risk rating as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014:
</P>

	In addition to the TDRs that occurred during the period provided in the preceding tables, the
	Company had TDRs with pre-modification loan balances of $3.4 million and zero as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, for which other real estate owned (&#147;OREO&#148;) was received in full or partial satisfaction of the loans. The
	majority of such TDRs were in commercial real estate and residential real estate as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had $3.5 million of OREO secured by residential real estate properties.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Allowance for Loan Losses, Credit Quality and Other for Covered Loans
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the 2015 quarterly impairment testing on the estimated cash flows of the covered loans, the Company established that certain pools
	evaluated had experienced material projected credit deterioration. As a result, the Company recorded a $998,000 net provision for loan losses to the allowance for loan losses related to the purchased credit impaired loans during the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 on a net basis. The Company also recorded a provision for loan loss of $2.5 million before benefit attributable to FDIC loss share agreements. Since these loans are covered by loss share with the FDIC, the Company was able to
	increase the related indemnification asset by $1.5 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the 2014 quarterly impairment testing on the estimated cash flows of
	the covered loans, the Company established that certain pools evaluated had experienced material projected credit deterioration. As a result, the Company recorded a $904,000 net provision for loan losses to the allowance for loan losses related to
	the purchased credit impaired loans during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 on a net basis. The Company also recorded a $1.2 million of provision for loan losses forecasted outside of loss share and a negative provision for loan loss of $1.4
	million before benefit attributable to FDIC loss share agreements. Since these loans are covered by loss share with the FDIC, the Company was able to decrease the related indemnification asset by $1.1 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the 2014 quarterly impairment testing on the estimated cash flows of the covered loans, the Company established that certain
	loss-sharing pools evaluated from the 2010 Old Southern and Key West acquisitions had experienced material projected credit improvement. As a result, the Company is recognizing $9.0 million of additional yield over the weighted average life of the
	loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the 2013 quarterly impairment testing on the estimated cash flows of the covered loans, the Company established that six
	pools evaluated had experienced material projected credit deterioration. As a result, the Company recorded a $4.4 million provision for loan losses to the allowance for loan losses related to the purchased impaired loans during the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2013. Since these loans are covered by loss share with the FDIC, the Company was able to increase the related indemnification asset by $3.5 million resulting in a net provision for loan losses of $991,000.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	141

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following tables present the balance in the allowance for loan losses for the covered loan
	portfolio for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, and the allowance for loan losses and recorded investment in loans covered by FDIC loss share based on portfolio segment by impairment method as of December&nbsp;31, 2014. Allocation of a portion
	of the allowance to one type of loan does not preclude its availability to absorb losses in other categories.
</P>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">

	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following tables present the balance in the allowance for loan losses for the covered loan
	portfolio for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, and the allowance for loan losses and recorded investment in loans covered by FDIC loss share based on portfolio segment by impairment method as of December&nbsp;31, 2013. Allocation of a portion
	of the allowance to one type of loan does not preclude its availability to absorb losses in other categories.
</P>

<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:8.0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:2PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;WIDTH:10%">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	At acquisition, 100% of the loans acquired from Old Southern, Key West, Coastal, Bayside, Wakulla and Gulf State were recorded for as purchased credit impaired loans on a pool by pool basis during 2010. During 2015, the
	five-year loss-share for Old Southern, Key West, Coastal, Bayside, Wakulla and Gulf State ended. Since the five-year covered loan loss-share has ended, the pools have been reevaluated and are no longer deemed to have a material projected credit
	impairment. As such, the remaining loans in these pools are performing and have been reclassified out of purchased credit impaired loans.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The non-covered purchased credit impaired loans acquired during the 2015 Doral Florida acquisition were deemed immaterial and as a result were
	not included in the table above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The loan pools were evaluated by the Company and are currently forecasted to have a slower run-off than
	originally expected. As a result, the Company has reforecast the total accretable yield expectations for those loan pools by $10.1 million. This updated forecast does not change the expected weighted average yields on the loan pools.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the 2015 impairment tests on the estimated cash flows of non-loss-share loans, we established that several non-covered loan pools were
	determined to have a materially projected credit improvement. As a result of this improvement, we will recognize approximately $28.5 million as an additional adjustment to yield over the weighted average life of the loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	7. Goodwill and Core Deposits and Other Intangibles
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Changes in the carrying amount and accumulated amortization of the Company&#146;s goodwill and core deposits and other
	intangibles at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, were as follows:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Core deposit and other intangible amortization expense for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and
	2013 was approximately $4.1 million, $4.6 million and $3.6 million, respectively. Core deposit and other intangibles are tested annually for impairment during the fourth quarter. During the 2015 review, no impairment was found. Including all of the
	mergers completed as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, HBI&#146;s estimated amortization expense of core deposits and other intangibles for each of the years 2016 through 2020 is approximately: 2016 - $3.1 million; 2017 - $3.0 million; 2018 - $2.9 million;
	2019 - $2.8 million; 2020 - $2.3 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The carrying amount of the Company&#146;s goodwill was $378.0 million and $325.4 million at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. Goodwill is tested annually for impairment during the fourth quarter. If the implied fair value of goodwill is lower than its carrying amount, goodwill impairment is indicated and goodwill is written
	down to its implied fair value. Subsequent increases in goodwill value are not recognized in the financial statements. During the 2015 review, no impairment was found.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	8. Other Assets
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Other assets consists primarily of FDIC claims receivable, equity securities without a readily determinable fair value and
	other miscellaneous assets. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 other assets were $117.9 million and $93.7 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	An
	indemnification asset was created when the Company acquired FDIC covered loans. The indemnification asset represents the carrying amount of the right to receive payments from the FDIC for losses incurred on specified assets acquired from failed
	insured depository institutions or otherwise purchased from the FDIC that are covered by loss-sharing agreements with the FDIC. When the Company experiences a loss on the covered loans and subsequently requests reimbursement of the loss from the
	FDIC, the indemnification asset is reduced by the FDIC reimbursable amount. A corresponding claim receivable is consequently recorded in other assets until the cash is received from the FDIC. The FDIC claims receivable was $3.2 million and $14.0
	million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company has equity securities without readily determinable fair values.
	These equity securities are outside the scope of FASB ASC Topic 320,
<I>
	Investments-Debt and Equity Securities
</I>
	. They include items such as stock holding in Federal Home Loan Bank, Federal Reserve Bank, Bankers&#146; Bank and other miscellaneous
	holdings. The equity securities without a readily determinable fair value were $97.5 million and $66.7 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively and are accounted for at cost.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	9. Deposits
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The aggregate amount of time deposits with a minimum denomination of $250,000 was $503.3 million and $272.5 million at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. The aggregate amount of time deposits with a minimum denomination of $100,000 was $885.3 million and $673.3 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. Interest expense applicable to
	certificates in excess of $100,000 totaled $5.0 million, $7.5 million and $4.1 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, brokered deposits were $199.3 million and $33.6
	million, respectively.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	10. Securities Sold Under Agreements to Repurchase

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, securities sold under agreements to repurchase totaled $128.4 million and $176.5
	million, respectively. For the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, securities sold under agreements to repurchase daily weighted-average totaled $156.5 million and $151.6 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	11. FHLB Borrowed Funds
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company&#146;s FHLB borrowed funds, which are secured by our loan portfolio, were $1.41 billion and $698.0 million at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, all $1.41 billion of the outstanding balance were issued as long-term advances. At December&nbsp;31, 2014, $515.0 million and $183.0 million of the outstanding balances were
	short-term and long-term advances, respectively. The FHLB advances mature from the current year to 2025 with fixed interest rates ranging from 0.14% to 5.96% and are secured by loans and investments securities. Expected maturities will differ from
	contractual maturities because FHLB may have the right to call or HBI the right to prepay certain obligations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Additionally, the Company
	had $261.1 million and $144.0 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, in letters of credit under a FHLB blanket borrowing line of credit, which are used to collateralize public deposits at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014,
	respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Maturities of borrowings with original maturities exceeding one year at December&nbsp;31, 2015, are as follows (in
	thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	12. Subordinated Debentures
</B>
</P>

	148
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage149"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company holds $60.8 million of trust preferred securities which are currently callable
	without penalty based on the terms of the specific agreements. The trust preferred securities are tax-advantaged issues that qualify for Tier 1 capital treatment subject to certain limitations. Distributions on these securities are included in
	interest expense. Each of the trusts is a statutory business trust organized for the sole purpose of issuing trust securities and investing the proceeds in the Company&#146;s subordinated debentures, the sole asset of each trust. The trust preferred
	securities of each trust represent preferred beneficial interests in the assets of the respective trusts and are subject to mandatory redemption upon payment of the subordinated debentures held by the trust. The Company wholly owns the common
	securities of each trust. Each trust&#146;s ability to pay amounts due on the trust preferred securities is solely dependent upon the Company making payment on the related subordinated debentures. The Company&#146;s obligations under the
	subordinated securities and other relevant trust agreements, in aggregate, constitute a full and unconditional guarantee by the Company of each respective trust&#146;s obligations under the trust securities issued by each respective trust.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	13. Other Borrowings
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2015, the parent company took out a $20.0 million line of credit for general corporate purposes. The balance on this
	line of credit at December&nbsp;31, 2015 was zero.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	14. Income Taxes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013:

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company and its subsidiaries file income tax returns in the U.S. federal jurisdiction and the states of
	Arkansas, Alabama and Florida and will be filing with the state of New York for the 2015 tax year beginning in 2016. The Company is no longer subject to U.S. federal and state tax examinations by tax authorities for years before 2011. During 2015,
	the State of Florida&#146;s examination of the Company&#146;s Florida State income tax returns for the 2010, 2011, 2012 and 2013 tax years was completed with no change to the financial position.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company recognizes interest accrued related to unrecognized tax benefits and penalties in income tax expense. During the years ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, the Company did not recognize any significant interest or penalties. The Company did not have any interest or penalties accrued at December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	15. Common Stock and Compensation Plans
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Common Stock
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;18, 2013 at the Annual Meeting of Shareholders of the Company, the shareholders approved, as proposed in the Proxy Statement, an
	amendment to the Company&#146;s Restated Articles of Incorporation to increase the number of authorized shares of common stock from 50,000,000 to 100,000,000.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;18, 2013, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors declared a 2-for-1 stock split to be paid in the form of a 100% stock dividend
	on June&nbsp;12, 2013 (the &#147;Payment Date&#148;) to shareholders of record at the close of business on May&nbsp;22, 2013. The additional shares were distributed by the Company&#146;s transfer agent, Computershare, and the Company&#146;s common
	stock began trading on a split-adjusted basis on the NASDAQ Global Select Market on June&nbsp;13, 2013. The stock split increased the Company&#146;s total shares of common stock outstanding as of June&nbsp;12, 2013 from 28,121,596 shares to
	56,243,192 shares. All previously reported share and per share data included in filings subsequent to the Payment Date are restated to reflect the retroactive effect of this 2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	150
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage151"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Stock Compensation Plans
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company has a stock option and performance incentive plan known as the Amended and Restated 2006 Stock Option and Performance Incentive
	Plan (&#147;the Plan&#148;). The purpose of the Plan is to attract and retain highly qualified officers, directors, key employees, and other persons, and to motivate those persons to improve the Company&#146;s business results. The Plan provides for
	the granting of incentive and non-qualified stock options and other equity awards, including the issuance of restricted shares. The maximum total number of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock available for grants under the Plan is 4,644,000.
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company has approximately 511,000 shares of common stock remaining available for future grants and approximately 1,908,000 shares of common stock reserved for issuance under the Plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The intrinsic value of the stock options outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013 was $21.1 million, $18.6 million and $26.8
	million, respectively. The intrinsic value of the stock options vested at December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 was $14.5 million, $15.9 million and $22.1 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The intrinsic value of the stock options exercised during 2015, 2014 and 2013 was $7.2 million, $3.2 million, and $2.2 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Total unrecognized compensation cost, net of income tax benefit, related to non-vested awards, which are expected to be recognized over
	the vesting periods, was approximately $7.4 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The table below summarized the stock option
	transactions under the Plan at December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 and changes during the years then ended:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Stock-based compensation expense for stock-based compensation awards granted is based on the grant-date fair
	value. For stock option awards, the fair value is estimated at the date of grant using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model. This model requires the input of highly subjective assumptions, changes to which can materially affect the fair value
	estimate. Additionally, there may be other factors that would otherwise have a significant effect on the value of employee stock options granted but are not considered by the model. Accordingly, while management believes that the Black-Scholes
	option-pricing model provides a reasonable estimate of fair value, the model does not necessarily provide the best single measure of fair value for the Company&#146;s employee stock options. The weighted-average fair value of options granted during
	the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 was $8.56 per share and $10.73 per share, respectively. The fair value of each option granted is estimated on the date of grant using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model based on the
	weighted-average assumptions for expected dividend yield, expected stock price volatility, risk-free interest rate, and expected life of options granted.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	151
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On August&nbsp;2, 2012, 208,000 shares of restricted common stock were issued to our named executive officers
	and certain other employees of the Company. These shares include 86,000 shares subject to time vesting (&#147;Restricted Shares&#148;) and 122,000 shares subject to performance based vesting (&#147;Performance Shares&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Restricted Shares will &#147;cliff&#148; vest on the third annual anniversary of the grant date. The Performance Shares are set up to
	&#147;cliff&#148; vest on the third annual anniversary of the date that the performance goal is met. As of September&nbsp;30, 2013, the performance goal was met when the Company averaged $0.3125 diluted earnings per share for the past four
	consecutive quarters or total diluted earnings per share of $1.25 during the same period. In accordance with the vesting terms of the Performance Shares agreements, the issued shares are due to fully vest on September&nbsp;30, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	152
</P>

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On January&nbsp;18, 2013, 18,000 shares of restricted common stock were issued to each
	non-employee member of our Board of Directors and 4,000 shares of restricted common stock to a regional president of our bank subsidiary for a total issuance of 22,000 shares of restricted common stock. The restricted stock issued will vest equally
	each year over three years beginning on the first anniversary of the issuance.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On June&nbsp;4, 2013, 12,666 shares of restricted common
	stock were issued to a regional president of our bank subsidiary. Of these issued shares, 9,666 shares will vest equally each year over three years beginning on the first anniversary of the issuance. The remaining 3,000 shares are subject to the
	previously discussed performance-based vesting.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On January&nbsp;17, 2014, the Company granted 40,000 shares of the Company&#146;s
	restricted common stock to the Chairman, which will vest in three equal annual installments beginning on January&nbsp;17, 2015, plus 3,000 restricted shares of HBI&#146;s common stock to a regional president of the Company&#146;s bank subsidiary,
	which will &#147;cliff&#148; vest on January&nbsp;17, 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On June&nbsp;23, 2014, the Company granted 500 shares of HBI&#146;s
	restricted common stock to an employee, which will vest in five equal annual installments beginning on June&nbsp;23, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On
	January&nbsp;16, 2015, the Company granted 60,000 shares of the Company&#146;s restricted common stock to the Chairman, 9,000 shares of restricted common stock to nine non-employee members of the Board of Directors and 3,992 shares of restricted
	common stock to a group of employees of the Company&#146;s bank subsidiary for a total issuance of 72,992 shares of restricted common stock. The restricted stock issued will &#147;cliff&#148; vest on January&nbsp;16, 2018.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On May&nbsp;28, 2015, the Company granted a total of 37,000 shares of the Company&#146;s restricted common stock to a group of employees of
	the Company&#146;s bank subsidiary. Of these issued shares, 18,500 shares will vest equally each year over three years beginning on the third anniversary of the grant. The remaining 18,500 shares are subject to performance based vesting (&#147;2015
	Performance Shares&#148;). The 2015 Performance Shares are set up to vest over three years beginning on the third anniversary of the date that the performance goal is met. The performance goal will be met when the Company averages $0.625 diluted
	earnings per share for four consecutive quarters or total diluted earnings per share of $2.50 during the same period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On August&nbsp;6,
	2015, the Company granted a total of 1,000 shares of the Company&#146;s restricted common stock to its recently named Chief Accounting Officer. The restricted stock issued will &#147;cliff&#148; vest on August&nbsp;6, 2018.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On August&nbsp;24, 2015, the Company granted a total of 220,000 shares of the Company&#146;s restricted common stock to a group of employees
	of the Company&#146;s bank subsidiary. Of these issued shares, 110,000 shares will vest equally each year over three years beginning on the third anniversary of the grant. The remaining 110,000 shares are subject to performance based vesting
	(&#147;2015 Performance Shares&#148;). The 2015 Performance Shares are set up to vest over three years beginning on the third anniversary of the date that the performance goal is met. The performance goal will be met when the Company averages $0.625
	diluted earnings per share for four consecutive quarters or total diluted earnings per share of $2.50 during the same period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October
	1, 2015, the Company granted a total of 10,000 shares of the Company&#146;s restricted common stock to an employee in connection with the acquisition of FBBI. The restricted stock issued will &#147;cliff&#148; vest on October 1, 2018. On December
	31, 2015, these shares were forfeited due to the employee&#146;s resignation from the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;9, 2015, the Company
	granted a total of 20,000 shares of the Company&#146;s restricted common stock to a group of employees of the Company&#146;s bank subsidiary. Of these issued shares, 10,000 shares will vest equally each year over three years beginning on the third
	anniversary of the grant. The remaining 10,000 shares are subject to performance based vesting (&#147;2015 Performance Shares&#148;). The 2015 Performance Shares are set up to vest over three years beginning on the third anniversary of the date that
	the performance goal is met. The performance goal will be met when the Company averages $0.625 diluted earnings per share for four consecutive quarters or total diluted earnings per share of $2.50 during the same period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2015, the Company utilized a portion of its previously approved stock repurchase program.
	This program authorized the repurchase of 2,376,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock. During the first quarter of 2015, the Company repurchased a total of 67,332 shares with a weighted-average stock price of $29.89 per share. No shares were
	repurchased after the first quarter of 2015. The 2015 earnings were used to fund these repurchases. Shares repurchased to date under the program total 1,578,228 shares. The remaining balance available for repurchase is 797,772 shares at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015. The Company did not utilize a portion of its previously approved stock repurchase program during 2014 or 2013.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	17. Employee Benefit Plans
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	401(k) Plan
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company has a retirement savings 401(k) plan in which substantially all employees may participate. The Company matches employees&#146;
	contributions based on a percentage of salary contributed by participants. While the plan also allows for discretionary employer contributions, no discretionary contributions were made for the years ended 2015, 2014 and 2013. The Company&#146;s
	expense for the plan was approximately $1.2 million, $1.0 million and $702,000 in 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively, which is included in salaries and employee benefits expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	154
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage155"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D86875D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Chairman&#146;s Retirement Plan
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;20, 2007, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors approved a Chairman&#146;s Retirement Plan for John W. Allison, the
	Company&#146;s Chairman. The Chairman&#146;s Retirement Plan provides a supplemental retirement benefit of $250,000 a year for 10 consecutive years or until Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s death, whichever occurs later. During 2011, Mr.&nbsp;Allison reached
	the age of 65 and became 100% vested in the plan. Therefore, he began receiving the supplemental retirement benefit due to him. He received $250,000 of this benefit during 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively. An expense of approximately $163,000,
	$169,000 and $176,000 was accrued for 2015, 2014 and 2013 for this plan, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	18. Related Party Transactions
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In the ordinary course of business, loans may be made to officers and directors and their affiliated companies at
	substantially the same terms as comparable transactions with other borrowers. At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, related party loans were approximately $51.2 million and $28.0 million, respectively. New loans and advances on prior commitments made
	to the related parties were $26.9&nbsp;million and $17.7 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. Repayments of loans made by the related parties were $3.7&nbsp;million and $20.3 million for the years ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, directors, officers, and other related interest
	parties had demand, non-interest-bearing deposits of approximately $590,000 and $8.9 million, respectively, savings and interest-bearing transaction accounts of approximately $11.0 million and $9.8 million, respectively, and time certificates of
	deposit of approximately $6.4 million and $8.0 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2015, 2014 and 2013, rent expense totaling approximately
	$100,000, $104,000 and $98,000, respectively, was paid to related parties.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	19. Leases
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company leases certain premises and equipment under noncancelable operating leases with terms up to 17 years which are
	charged to expense over the lease term as it becomes payable. The Company&#146;s leases do not have rent holidays. In addition, any rent escalations are tied to the consumer price index or contain nominal increases and are not included in the
	calculation of current lease expense due to the immaterial amount. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the minimum rental commitments under these noncancelable operating leases are as follows (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
